  "answer": "**Iqbal — strongest khudi verse in corpus:**\n\nThe corpus contains only Bang-e-Dara (Parts 1–3); Asrar-e-Khudi, Iqbal's primary khudi text, is not present. The closest verse in Bang-e-Dara to the claim that the self is built, not given, is in **Bang-e-Dara Part 3, Chapter 12 \"Insaan\" (The Human Being)** [allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, ch. 12]:\n\n> [p-cb3c43] \"Whatever exists in the world is accustomed to submission; Every power of the Human Being is aflame with striving.\"\n> [p-587d8c] \"If it so chooses, it can change the very form of the garden; This being is wise, is perceptive, is potent.\"\n\nThis poem makes the key khudi distinction explicit: all other creation is fixed in submission (its nature is given), while the Human Being's powers are \"aflame with striving\" — i.e., constituted through action, not inheritance. The phrase \"if it so chooses\" asserts radical self-determination. This is as close as Bang-e-Dara comes to Asrar-e-Khudi's programmatic claim that khudi is forged through effort, love, and sustained will — not received by birth.\n\n---\n\n**Manu — strongest varna-as-given verse:**\n\n**Manusmrti Chapter 1, verse Mn_1.31** [unknown-manusmrti-347b76, ch. 1, p-13a2db]:\n\n> \"And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.\"\n\nThis is the cosmogonic origin of the varna system. The four social classes literally proceed from the body of the Creator — mouth, arms, thighs, feet — making social location a cosmic fact of origin, not an achievement. The doctrine is reinforced at Mn_1.93 [p-7c0113]:\n\n> \"By his origin from the highest limb, by his seniority, and by his preservation of the Veda, the Brahmana is by right the lord of this whole creation.\"\n\nHere, the ground of lordship is not merit but \"origin from the highest limb.\" Social location is guaranteed by where in the Creator's body your class type originated — the most fully given claim possible.\n\n---\n\n**Which is harder to hold honestly?**\n\nManu's varna-dharma is the harder doctrine to hold honestly.\n\nKhudi's claim — that the self is constructed through striving — is at least empirically grounded in part. People do build themselves through disciplined effort, love, and sustained practice. The difficulty of holding khudi is existential: it demands you own your self completely, including its mediocrity and failures. But as a belief, its epistemic footing is sound — it describes a real phenomenon, even if few fully achieve it.\n\nVarna-dharma's claim — that birth from a specific cosmic body-part determines your entire social location, worth, and duty — requires surrendering ordinary epistemic standards. To hold it honestly, a Brahmin must look at the actual distribution of capability, virtue, and insight across birth-castes and still maintain: \"My pre-eminence is given by my origin from Brahma's mouth.\" This requires either deep pre-critical cosmological faith or motivated rationalization of hereditary privilege as cosmic justice.\n\nThe Manusmrti itself quietly undermines the absolute doctrine. At Mn_10.65, Manu concedes that a Shudra can attain Brahmin status and vice versa across generations — the hereditary lines are not perfectly rigid. Mn_1.31's clean cosmogonic certainty is already in tension with Mn_10's more complex genealogical accounting.\n\nIn sum: khudi is the harder doctrine to *practice* (it demands relentless self-construction, no blame-shifting to birth or circumstance). Varna-dharma is the harder doctrine to *hold honestly* — it asserts that cosmic genetics determines human worth, a claim that honest confrontation with evidence and moral intuition cannot sustain without bad faith.",
