**Summary of findings:**

**Iqbal (corpus caveat):** Asrar-e-Khudi is not in the corpus — only Bang-e-Dara Parts 1–3 are present. The strongest khudi-adjacent verse found is Bang-e-Dara Part 3, ch. 12 "Insaan" [p-cb3c43 / p-587d8c]: *"Whatever exists in the world is accustomed to submission; Every power of the Human Being is aflame with striving… If it so chooses, it can change the very form of the garden."* This makes the core khudi distinction — all other creation is fixed in given nature; the Human Being is constituted through striving and choice.

**Manu:** Manusmrti ch. 1, Mn_1.31 [p-13a2db]: *"he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet."* Social location is cosmogonically assigned — the four varnas originate from specific body parts of the Creator. Mn_1.93 reinforces this: the Brahmin's lordship comes from "origin from the highest limb," not from merit.

**Harder doctrine:** Manu's varna-dharma is harder to hold honestly. Khudi is harder to *practice* (it demands total self-ownership). Varna-dharma is harder to *believe honestly* — it requires maintaining that an accident of birth (from which cosmic body-part your class originates) determines human worth, a claim the Manusmrti itself partially undermines by the time we reach Chapter 10.
